1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 (5... b5 6. Bb3 Bc5 {
The archangel doesn't always lead to this structure, but it did in this
instructive game from the black side.} 7. c3 d6 8. d4 Bb6 9. Be3 O-O 10. Nbd2
Bb7 11. Re1 exd4 12. cxd4 Nb4 13. Qe2 c5 {[%csl Gc5,Gd4,Gd6,Ge4] Black
challenges White's center.} 14. a3 Nc6 15. d5 Ne7 16. h3 Re8 17. Bc2 Ng6 18. b3
{Black has a great idea here.} Ba5 $1 19. Rab1 Bc3 {[%cal Gc3e5] As in other
positions of this sort, this bishop belongs on this diagonal.} 20. Rec1 b4 21.
a4 a5 22. Bd3 {White controls c4, but has little else that is positive about
his position.} h6 23. Qd1 Ba6 24. Bc2 Ra7 25. Kh2 Rae7 26. g4 Nxe4 $1 27. Nxe4
Rxe4 28. Bxe4 Rxe4 29. Qc2 Qe7 30. Rg1 Rxe3 31. fxe3 Qxe3 32. Rbf1 Be2 33. Qf5
Bd3 34. Qd7 Be5+ 35. Kh1 Be4 36. Qe8+ Nf8 {Karjakin - Caruana 0-1, Bilbao 2012}
) 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 Bb7 10. d4 Re8 11. Nbd2 Bf8 (11... exd4
12. cxd4 Nd7 13. Nf1 Na5 14. Bc2 Bf6 15. Rb1 c5 {[%csl Gc5,Gd4,Gd6,Ge4] is yet
another way to get this structure.} 16. d5 Nc4 $1 {Fixing the knight on a5 is
usually important.} 17. b3 Nce5 18. N3h2 Bc8 19. Ne3 Nb6 20. Bb2 a5 21. Nf3 Ng6
22. Bd3 Bd7 23. Nd2 a4 24. Bf1 axb3 25. axb3 Bxb2 26. Rxb2 Qf6 27. Rc2 Ra7 28.
g3 Qd4 29. Qe2 Ra1 30. Rcc1 Ra2 31. Rc2 Ra1 32. Rcc1 Ra2 {1/2-1/2 (32)
Ivanchuk,V (2726)-Kovalev,V (2639) Riyadh KSA 2017}) 12. a4 h6 13. Bc2 exd4 14.
cxd4 Nb4 15. Bb1 c5 {[%csl Gc5,Gd4,Gd6,Ge4] This is a combative pawn structure
where both sides have chances for advantage. Black often has better queenside
chances, but without appropriate caution White can build a powerful kingside
initiative.} 16. d5 Nd7 17. Ra3 c4 18. Nd4 (18. axb5 axb5 19. Nd4 Qb6 20. Nf5
Ne5 21. Rg3 g6 22. Nf3 Ned3 23. Qd2 Bxd5 $2 {This one error leads to a lost
position.} (23... Nxe1 {is more accurate, and leads ot a draw by perpetual.}
24. Nxe1 Ra1 25. Nxh6+ Bxh6 26. Qxh6 Nxd5 27. Rxg6+ fxg6 28. Qxg6+) 24. Nxh6+
Bxh6 25. Qxh6 Qxf2+ 26. Kh2 Nxe1 27. Nh4 Ned3 28. Nxg6 Qxg3+ 29. Kxg3 fxg6 30.
Qxg6+ Kf8 31. Qf6+ Kg8 32. Bh6 {1-0 (32) Anand,V (2788)-Adams,M (2719) San
Luis 2005}) 18... Qf6 19. N2f3 Nc5 20. axb5 axb5 21. Nxb5 Rxa3 22. Nxa3 Ba6 23.
Re3 Rb8 24. Nd4 Nbd3 {Anand has sacrificed a pawn, but the knight on d3 is a
monster.} 25. Bxd3 Nxd3 26. Rxd3 cxd3 27. Nc6 Rxb2 28. Bxb2 Qxb2 29. Nb1 g6 30.
Nd2 h5 31. Nf3 Bc4 32. Qa4 Qc1+ 33. Kh2 Qf4+ 34. Kg1 Qxe4 35. Na5 Bxd5 36. Qxe4
Bxe4 37. Nd2 Bd5 38. Kf1 Bh6 39. Nb1 d2 40. Nc3 Bg7 41. Nd1 Bd4 {0-1 (41)
Shirov,A (2739)-Anand,V (2801) Moscow 2007} *

